99–6 October 1448":"12 May 1399–6 October 1448","1390–1458":"1390–1458","1420–1459":"1420–1459","1422–1442":"1422–1442","1434–Female":"1434–Deceased","1436–Female":"1436–Deceased","1438–Female":"1438–Deceased","1399–1448":"1399–1448","14Aug1436":"14 August 1436","29 October 1422":"29 October 1422","18 May 1434":"18 May 1434","12 May 1399":"12 May 1399","1390":"1390","1448":"1448","1459":"1459","27 June 1442":"27 June 1442","1436":"1436","1458":"1458","1434":"1434","1422":"1422","1399":"1399","ABT 1420":"about 1420","1442":"1442","1420":"1420","6 October 1448":"6 October 1448","1438":"1438","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Stittenham, Yorkshire, England":"Stittenham, Yorkshire, England","of, Woodhall, Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","France":"France","Stittenham, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Stittenham, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan was born on 12 May 1399, in France. She had at least 2 sons and 3 daughters with Thomas Gower, Esq. She died on 6 October 1448, at the age of 49."},"et":{"12 May 1399–6 October 1448":"12. mai 1399–6. oktoober 1448","1390–1458":"1390–1458","1420–1459":"1420–1459","1422–1442":"1422–1442","1434–Female":"1434–Surnud","1436–Female":"1436–Surnud","1438–Female":"1438–Surnud","1399–1448":"1399–1448","14Aug1436":"14. august 1436","29 October 1422":"29. oktoober 1422","18 May 1434":"18. mai 1434","12 May 1399":"12. mai 1399","1390":"1390","1448":"1448","1459":"1459","27 June 1442":"27. juuni 1442","1436":"1436","1458":"1458","1434":"1434","1422":"1422","1399":"1399","ABT 1420":"umbes 1420","1442":"1442","1420":"1420","6 October 1448":"6. oktoober 1448","1438":"1438","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Stittenham, Yorkshire, England":"Stittenham, Yorkshire, England","of, Woodhall, Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","France":"Prantsusmaa","Stittenham, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Stittenham, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"12 May 1399–6 October 1448":"12. toukokuuta 1399–6. lokakuuta 1448","1390–1458":"1390–1458","1420–1459":"1420–1459","1422–1442":"1422–1442","1434–Female":"1434–Kuollut","1436–Female":"1436–Kuollut","1438–Female":"1438–Kuollut","1399–1448":"1399–1448","14Aug1436":"14. 